CHAPTER ______
1 AN ACT concerning
2 Health Occupations – Human Trafficking Awareness Training
3 FOR the purpose of requiring each health occupations board to allow an applicant to receive
4 continuing education credits for completing a certain human trafficking awareness
5 training program, adopt certain regulations, and conduct certain outreach related to
6 continuing education credits for a certain human trafficking awareness training
7 program; establishing requirements for the training program; and generally relating
8 to human trafficking awareness training for health care practitioners.
9 BY adding to
10 Article – Health Occupations
11 Section 1–225.1
12 Annotated Code of Maryland
13 (2021 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
14 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
15 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
16 Article – Health Occupations
17 1–225.1.
EXPLANATION: CAPITALS INDICATE MATTER ADDED TO EXISTING LAW.
[Brackets] indicate matter deleted from existing law.
Underlining indicates amendments to bill.
Strike out indicates matter stricken from the bill by amendment or deleted from the law by
amendment. *hb0771*

2 HOUSE BILL 771
1 (A) (1) IN THIS SECTION, “LOCAL UNIVERSITY” MEANS A PUBLIC OR
2 PRIVATE INSTITUTION OF HIGHER EDUCATION IN THE STATE WITH A PUBLIC
3 HEALTH, LAW, OR SOCIAL WORK PROGRAM.
4 (2) “LOCAL UNIVERSITY” INCLUDES A PROGRAM WITHIN AN
5 INSTITUTION OF HIGHER EDUCATION DESCRIBED IN PARAGRAPH (1) OF THIS
6 SUBSECTION, SUCH AS THE UNIVERSITY OF MARYLAND SAFE CENTER FOR HUMAN
7 TRAFFICKING SURVIVORS.
8 (B) EACH HEALTH OCCUPATIONS BOARD SHALL:
9 (1) ADOPT REGULATIONS THAT ALLOW ALLOW AN APPLICANT
10 SEEKING LICENSE OR CERTIFICATE RENEWAL TO RECEIVE CONTINUING EDUCATION
11 CREDITS FOR COMPLETING A HUMAN TRAFFICKING AWARENESS TRAINING
12 PROGRAM DESCRIBED IN SUBSECTION (C) OF THIS SECTION; AND
13 (2) CONDUCT OUTREACH TO MAKE INDIVIDUALS REGULATED BY THE
14 BOARD AWARE OF HUMAN TRAFFICKING AWARENESS TRAINING OPTIONS,
15 INCLUDING BY PROVIDING INFORMATION IN GENERAL BOARD COMMUNICATIONS
16 AND ON THE BOARD’S WEBSITE; AND
17 (3) ADOPT REGULATIONS TO CARRY OUT THIS SECTION.
18 (C) A TRAINING PROGRAM FOR WHICH AN APPLICANT MAY RECEIVE
19 CONTINUING EDUCATION CREDITS UNDER THIS SECTION SHALL:
20 (1) BE APPROVED BY THE DEPARTMENT IN COLLABORATION WITH A
21 LOCAL UNIVERSITY AND IN CONSULTATION WITH THE MARYLAND HUMAN
22 TRAFFICKING TASK FORCE AND ORGANIZATIONS THAT PROVIDE DIRECT SERVICES
23 TO HUMAN TRAFFICKING SURVIVORS;
24 (2) BE AT LEAST 1 HOUR IN DURATION;
25 (3) BE READILY ACCESSIBLE AND PROVIDED TO AN INDIVIDUAL
26 DESCRIBED UNDER SUBSECTION (B) OF THIS SECTION FREE OF CHARGE; AND
27 (4) INCLUDE INSTRUCTION ON:
28 (I) THE DEFINITIONS AND FORMS OF SEX AND LABOR
29 TRAFFICKING UNDER FEDERAL AND STATE LAW;
30 (II) AN UNDERSTANDING OF THE TRAUMA–INFORMED CARE
31 MODEL;

HOUSE BILL 771 3
1 (III) THE PHYSICAL, BEHAVIORAL, AND EMOTIONAL
2 INDICATORS OF HUMAN TRAFFICKING, PARTICULARLY THOSE PRESENTING IN A
3 HEALTH CARE SETTING;
4 (IV) APPROPRIATE SCREENING PROTOCOLS AND
5 DOCUMENTATION METHODS;
6 (V) MANDATORY REPORTING REQUIREMENTS UNDER STATE
7 LAW AND ESTABLISHED PROTOCOLS FOR REPORTING SUSPECTED CASES OF HUMAN
8 TRAFFICKING TO THE APPROPRIATE AUTHORITIES, INCLUDING THE NATIONAL
9 HUMAN TRAFFICKING HOTLINE; AND
10 (VI) AVAILABLE FEDERAL, STATE, AND LOCAL RESOURCES AND
11 SERVICES FOR SURVIVORS OF HUMAN TRAFFICKING.
12 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That:
13 (a) On or before July 1, 2026, the Maryland Department of Health, in
14 collaboration and consultation with required stakeholders, shall approve the training
15 program required under § 1–225.1 of the Health Occupations Article, as enacted under
16 Section 1 of this Act.
17 (b) On or before October January 1, 2026 2027, each health occupations board
18 shall adopt the regulations necessary to carry out required under § 1–225.1(b)(3) of the
19 Health Occupations Article, as enacted by this Act.
20 SECTION 3. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect June
21 1, 2026.
Approved:
